<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOOD AND COMMON SENSE: ANALYZING DIETARY LINKS TO ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JEAN MAYER and JEANNE GOLDBERG 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
You're introduced to someone new, but before you complete the handshake you've 
forgotten her name. Or you spend a good part of your day searching for "lost" 
items -- car keys, eyeglasses, a pen. All of us experience occasional lapses of 
memory and may joke that we're "getting Alzheimer's." In most cases we simply 
haven't been paying attention and focusing on the task at hand. 
</P>
<P>
But for the million or more victims of Alzheimer's disease in the United States 
and their families, this condition is no laughing matter, and it involves a 
great deal more than just inattention. 
</P>
<P>
Alzheimer's is a progressive neurological disorder in which nerve pathways that 
carry messages within the brain become tangled and blocked by plaques. The 
production of certain chemicals, known as neurotransmitters, used by nerve 
cells to communicate with each other, is reduced. When normal nerve signals 
can't be relayed, depression, delusions, agitation, weight loss and changes in 
memory, may result. 
</P>
<P>
Although more prevalent in older people, Alzheimer's is sometimes seen in 
persons younger than 50. Since it frequently occurs in families and in those 
with Down's syndrome who live past 40, a genetic component is suspected. 
</P>
<P>
Fear of the enormous physical and psychological toll that this disease exacts 
has spawned numerous nutrition practices that claim to help prevent onset or 
minimize symptoms. One compound that has received attention is choline. 
Contrary to some claims, choline is not a vitamin for humans under normal 
circumstances. Our livers are able to make enough to meet our needs. Additional 
choline is also found in foods such as milk, egg yolks, dried beans and peas, 
and foods containing lecithin. 
</P>
<P>
As its name suggests, choline is a component of the neurotransmitter 
acetcylcholine, as well as of certain cell structures, so it's not absurd to 
speculate that supplements might help reduce symptoms of Alzheimer's. 
Unfortunately, most research shows that supplementing the diets of Alzheimer's 
patients with either choline or lecithin produces scant improvement in memory 
and may aggravate depression. 
</P>
<P>
While many persons fearful of Alzheimer's have been popping choline and 
lecithin supplements, others have been attempting to purge their diets of the 
mineral aluminum. Humans have no known nutritional requirement for aluminum. 
But as the third most common element in the earth's crust, it is widely 
available in most grains and vegetables and in drinking water, with small 
quantities occurring in animal products. 
</P>
<P>
Aluminum-containing compounds are often used as food additives and may be found 
in food colorings and certain brands of salt and baking powder. Aluminum foil 
and cookware may also serve as sources of aluminum in food, although in most 
cases the aluminum contamination is minimal. Larger quantities may leach into 
food when tomato dishes such as spaghetti sauce or chili are simmered for hours 
in aluminum pots -- although the total amount the food might contain still 
remains low. 
</P>
<P>
For some, the greatest source of aluminum may be aluminum-containing antacids 
and buffered pain relievers, which may provide 50 times the amount obtained 
from foods. Still, most evidence suggests that healthy people generally can 
eliminate most dietary aluminum long before toxic effects set in. 
</P>
<P>
The real concern shouldn't be how much aluminum we consume but rather if it is 
contributing to Alzheimer's disease. Here the evidence is incomplete. 
</P>
<P>
Researchers have shown that high levels of aluminum in the blood can accumulate 
in the brain, producing a type of encephalopathy, or brain disorder. Recently, 
this type of condition has been seen in kidney patients receiving 
aluminum-containing antacids to help prevent bone disease. In the past, kidney 
patients undergoing dialysis, a procedure that mimics the role of kidneys by 
cleansing the blood of wastes, were at risk since the dialysis process also 
contaminated the blood with aluminum. In this case, when the kidneys are 
impaired, aluminum clearly produces toxic effects. 
</P>
<P>
But analysis of brains of Alzheimer's victims for aluminum accumulation has 
produced conflicting results. While some researchers have found high amounts of 
aluminum in the characteristic nerve tangles, this finding has been disputed. 
And even if scientists were confident that brain aluminum levels are elevated 
in Alzheimer's, no one knows which comes first, high aluminum or the disease. 
</P>
<P>
Some suspect that the degenerative changes taking place within the nerve cells 
of Alzheimer's patients actually promote aluminum buildup in the cells. Others 
speculate that aluminum may be involved in plaque development, since 
aluminum-containing compounds have been found at the core of these plaques, or 
that aluminum somehow contributes to the nerve-cell snarls. Obviously, more 
research is needed before the precise role of aluminum in Alzheimer's can be 
determined. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, you might wonder what you should do about aluminum cookware. The 
answer is, cook with it. And as always, cook nutritious wholesome foods. If 
you're really convinced your memory is slipping, see a doctor. But for most of 
us, forgetting at least part of what we should remember is a normal feature of 
everyday life. 
</P>
<P>
Question: I suffer terribly from stomach gas shortly after I eat. Are there any 
dietary steps I can take to help control it? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: The biggest culprits include large, calorie-laden meals, and fatty 
foods in particular, since they slow the rate at which foods leave the stomach. 
Carbonated beverages and chewing gum are also better set aside. In addition to 
all the other problems it causes, smoking is linked to increased air swallowing 
and gas production. If you've experienced symptoms commonly referred to as 
"heartburn," avoid fatty foods, alcohol, chocolate and pepper. 
</P>
<P>
You might also find some relief by modifying your eating behavior. If you tend 
to be a rapid eater, slow down. And while it's important to drink plenty of 
fluids, limit the amount with which you wash down food. 
</P>
<P>
Medications are sometimes used to reduce carbon dioxide production, but this is 
something you should discuss with a doctor. 
</P>
<P>
Q: Is there any evidence that development of diabetes is influenced by either 
the composition of the diet or levels of physical activity, or by some 
combination of the two? 
</P>
<P>
A: Studies have failed to find a consistent link between the composition of the 
diet and diabetes development. In part, this may be explained by the difficulty 
in obtaining accurate dietary information. Beyond that, unfortunately, many of 
the studies that have explored the question have failed to take into account 
the numerous other factors that could explain differences in incidence of 
diabetes between two populations or within subgroups of the same population. 
</P>
<P>
When it comes to physical activity, the picture is really no less certain, 
although such a relationship is biologically plausible. It's clear that 
exercise can modify the body's short-term ability to handle glucose and blood 
sugar. But there is only sparse and inconsistent evidence that long-term lack 
of exercise increases the risk of adult-onset diabetes. 
</P>
<P>
There are many reasons to argue for both a prudent diet -- rich in complex 
carbohydrates, low in fat, salt and sugar -- and for regular physical activity. 
But the question as to whether these measures can reduce the risk of 
adult-onset diabetes requires further research. 
</P>
<P>
Q: My daughter joined her high school swim team last semester. When I took her 
to the doctor, he discovered that she was anemic. Can the strenuous exercise 
also cause her problem? 
</P>
<P>
A: A recently reported small study of swimmers suggests a more direct 
explanation for your daughter's anemia: low iron intake. Investigators could 
find no evidence of changes in blood profiles at the end of a season of 
competition, suggesting that the muscular exercise of swimming does no damage 
to red blood cells. 
</P>
<P>
However, in that study, not one of the six women involved consumed even as much 
as 60% of the Recommended Dietary Allowances. Some consumed considerably less. 
Assessment of the relationship between iron intake and menstrual losses in 
these women indicated that about half of them simply were not taking adequate 
amounts to offset their losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
