<HEADLINE>
<P>
GROUP GAINS IN FIGHT ON BILLBOARDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTHA L. WILLMAN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In its first attempt to flex its political muscle, the Crescenta Valley Town 
Council has won a step in its battle to ban all new billboards in the 
semi-rural community. 
</P>
<P>
The Los Angeles County Regional Planning Commission voted unanimously last week 
to recommend establishment of a billboard exclusion zone in La Crescenta and 
Montrose, an isolated, unincorporated island of county territory sandwiched 
between Glendale and La Canada Flintridge. 
</P>
<P>
The action recommends that the County Board of Supervisors permanently prohibit 
construction of any new billboards in the La Crescenta area. Action by 
supervisors is expected in about a month. 
</P>
<P>
The billboard issue was the first undertaken by the nine-member advisory 
council, formed 16 months ago by residents in a grass-roots effort to gain 
greater say over their community. The council has no direct legislative power 
but acts as an adviser to County Supervisor Mike Antonovich. 
</P>
<P>
Residents had complained that giant billboards along Foothill and Oceanview 
boulevards, the main commercial strips, create a visual blight in the hillside 
community. Most of the billboards have cropped up in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
The proposed exclusion zone would prohibit all new signs. Existing signs could 
stay indefinitely, but could not be replaced or moved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA070590-0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 242943 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 5, 1990, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
