<HEADLINE>
<P>
IT'S SURPRISE, SURPRISE FOR PARENTS OF TWIN BOYS; 
</P>
<P>
BIRTHS: RITA AND BILL WILLIAMSON EXPECTED BIG BABIES, BUT ONE WEIGHED MORE THAN 
11 POUNDS, THE OTHER MORE THAN 9 POUNDS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LILY ENG, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LOS ALAMITOS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Big babies run in the Williamson family. But nobody was prepared for twin boys 
-- one 11 pounds, 8 ounces, the other, 9 pounds, 10 ounces -- least of all mom 
Rita Williamson. 
</P>
<P>
"I was all baby," said Rita Williamson, 27, who was resting Wednesday at the 
Los Alamitos Hospital birthing center. "I'm kind of tired now, so I'm glad it's 
over." 
</P>
<P>
Craig Allen and Thomas Arthur were born Monday by Cesarean section. Craig, the 
biggest, was first at 8:21 a.m. A minute later, little brother Thomas followed. 
Both measured more than 21 inches. 
</P>
<P>
"They're the largest twins the hospital has ever had," nursing supervisor 
Josephine Vantrees said. "They were pretty enormous." 
</P>
<P>
Twins usually average about six pounds. But the Williamson twins are bigger 
than most single-birth babies, which average around seven pounds. A single 
birth baby weighing more than nine pounds is considered large, Vantrees said. 
</P>
<P>
The twins and mom will join their sister, Tanya, 2, and dad, Bill, at home in 
Cerritos once Williamson recovers, which is expected to be within a few days. 
</P>
<P>
Rita Williamson said she tried to stay cool during the past two months, despite 
having to carry around 56 extra pounds. "I'm a pretty big woman to start with," 
she said, "but the babies added more around the tummy." 
</P>
<P>
She said the hardest part of her pregnancy came during the wave of triple-digit 
temperatures last month. She coped by wearing loose clothing, staying in 
air-conditioned rooms and doing as little as possible. Even just walking seemed 
like strenuous exercise. 
</P>
<P>
The couple discovered that two very big boys were on the way Friday, when Rita 
had an ultrasound test. 
</P>
<P>
"We expected them to be little guys 'cause, you know, they're twins," said Bill 
Williamson, a computer programmer. "But I guess we were more than lucky." 
</P>
<P>
By delivery time, the Williamsons were "geared for big babies." Rita had had 
some experience with an unusual birth -- Tanya had been 9 pounds, 12 ounces and 
in the breech position. 
</P>
<P>
"The two of them have already beaten me in a way," says Bill, who was 8 pounds, 
7 ounces at birth. "They got me by a couple of ounces. 
</P>
<P>
Bill already foresees a great future in football for his sons. Craig, the 
bigger one, is going to be a linebacker, and Thomas, no small potato himself, 
is going to be a lineman, he predicts. 
</P>
<P>
"We're waiting for USC to call," Williamson quipped. "I bet they can take 
crawlers for the next season." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, DOUBLE SURPRISE: Babies run large in the Williamson family, but 
the latest take the birthday cake: With mother, Rita, are Craig, left, at 11 
pounds, 8 ounces, and Thomas, 9 pounds, 10 ounces. ; Photo, Rita Williamson 
holds newborn sons Craig, left, and Thomas, right. Husband Bill and daughter 
Tanya, 2, visit the three at hospital. ROD BOREN / For The Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
