<HEADLINE>
<P>
DISNEY'S KCAL COMES UNDER FIRE; 
</P>
<P>
MARKETING: STATION'S ADVERTISING PLOY TO GET ITSELF ON SANTA BARBARA CABLE 
SYSTEM HAS ANGERED MANY IN THE FIRE-RAVAGED AREA. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE WEINSTEIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some TV officials in fire-ravaged Santa Barbara are burning mad at Los Angeles 
station KCAL Channel 9 for using the tragedy there last week as a marketing 
ploy to boost its own fortunes. 
</P>
<P>
The Disney-owned station took out a full-page ad in the Santa Barbara 
News-Press on Monday that championed KCAL's coverage of the city's devastating 
fire and asked Santa Barbara residents to call their cable company to ask that 
KCAL be added to the programming lineup. 
</P>
<P>
Cox Cable, which carries the other six Los Angeles VHF stations on its Santa 
Barbara system, called the ad "unconscionable" and "offensive." And sources at 
KEYT Channel 3, Santa Barbara's only local television station, said that many 
in their community are outraged that KCAL would try to capitalize on the 
tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
After seeing the ad in her hometown paper, Sandra Benton, the general manager 
of KEYT, an ABC affiliate that supplied KCAL with coverage of the fire before 
KCAL was able to rush its own personnel and equipment some 90 miles up the 
coast, sent a letter to KCAL general manager Blake Byrne chastising his station 
for the marketing move. 
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, KCAL said that it would air one hour of the six-hour fire relief 
telethon that KEYT plans to broadcast Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
Benton refused to speculate on whether KCAL's decision was an attempt to make 
up for a public relations blunder. But Bobbi Didier, director of public affairs 
at Cox Cable, saw it that way. "It's a nice effort, but it doesn't undo the 
damage they have already done," she said. 
</P>
<P>
Because of the Independence Day holiday, executives at KCAL were unavailable 
for comment. 
</P>
<P>
The telethon, which is designed to raise money for the victims of the Santa 
Barbara fire, will air live on KEYT and on Cox cable's Telemundo Spanish 
channel from 6 p.m. to midnight. KCAL will air the final hour of the telethon. 
</P>
<P>
The story behind the KCAL ad actually begins several years ago, prior to 
Disney's purchase of the station in 1988. Cox officials, citing the fact that 
the station, then KHJ, was garnering very low ratings in the Santa Barbara 
area, dropped it from the cable system to make way for other channels. That 
effectively shut off any opportunity of Channel 9 reaching viewers in the city, 
where the mountainous terrain makes cable a necessity for most homes. 
</P>
<P>
Just two weeks ago, however, Cox sent a survey to its 61,000 subscribers, 
asking them to rate their current programming choices and to comment on a list 
of new options, including KCAL, that they might like to receive. 
</P>
<P>
Rather than waiting for the results of the survey or appealing to Cox directly, 
KCAL took matters into its own hands by buying the ad in Monday's Santa Barbara 
News-Press. The ad featured a group photo of nine anchors and other members of 
the Channel 9 news team alongside copy that read: "Last week Santa Barbara and 
much of Southern California experienced horribly tragic fires. KCAL-TV, 
California 9, covered all of these fires in depth with: live reports, 
helicopter coverage, frequent live cut-ins, and most importantly, three full 
hours of coverage in prime time, 8-11 p.m., where we have local news every week 
day. Unfortunately, you can't get California 9 on your cable system." 
</P>
<P>
It then asked readers to call the Cox general manager at a phone number listed 
in the ad to request "that KCAL-TV be added to your cable system. Because what 
you don't know . . . can hurt you." 
</P>
<P>
KCAL did not run ads about its fire coverage in Los Angeles area newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
"Many people see it as an inappropriate lobbying effort to get themselves back 
on the cable system," said a KEYT employee who did not want to be identified. 
"It looked like they were trying to capitalize on our tragedy." 
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview, Benton refused to say anything negative about KCAL 
for fear of jeopardizing its commitment to air one hour of Saturday's telethon. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm thankful that they're going to run the telethon for whatever reason they 
are choosing to do it," she said. "I don't want to say anything that would hurt 
the good that might come out of that. We are so devastated and we are such a 
small community, everyone knows a friend or a co-worker here at the station who 
has lost their home." 
</P>
<P>
But Cox was pulling no punches. 
</P>
<P>
Since Disney bought the station, no one from KCAL or Disney has ever contacted 
Cox directly about their desire to be added to the system, Didier said. 
</P>
<P>
And to make matters worse, she said, the phone number that KCAL printed in the 
ad was not an administrative number, but Cox's customer service line, which was 
already swamped with calls from customers trying to get their cable service 
restored. Didier said that 16 1/2 miles of the cable system was destroyed by 
the fire, and that crews had been working around the clock to repair the 
damage. 
</P>
<P>
Giving out the customer service number to serve "their lust for profits," 
Didier said, resulted in unnecessary calls on a line already overburdened with 
requests for assistance from victims of the fire. 
</P>
<P>
"Forget about tasteless," she said. "The ad just continued to hurt Santa 
Barbara." 
</P>
<P>
As for the news coverage that KCAL claimed Santa Barbara viewers missed, KEYT 
news employees said that none of the Los Angeles stations were on the scene in 
time to get anything of their own on the air before about 10 p.m. the first 
evening, June 27. By that time, KEYT had already been supplying local residents 
with continuous coverage of the fire for 3 1/2 hours. The station stayed on the 
air with news from 6 p.m. to 3 a.m. KCAL finished its news reports at 11 p.m. 
Moreover, some of what KCAL aired from Santa Barbara was supplied by KEYT, 
which also shared videotape with KABC Channel 7 and KTTV Channel 11. 
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the Santa Barbara News-Press on behalf of Cox, Didier wrote: "If 
KCAL is so interested in Santa Barbara, they should put their resources into 
helping our fire victims, not buying expensive and offensive ads." 
</P>
<P>
Will such feelings keep KCAL from getting back on the Cox cable lineup? 
</P>
<P>
"If our customers tell us they want it, we would provide it for them," Didier 
said. "But I think now it would be more difficult to grin and bear them." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
TELEVISION STATIONS; SANTA BARBARA (CA); TELEVISION PROGRAMMING; BRUSH FIRES -- 
SANTA BARBARA COUNTY; MARKETING; ADVERTISING; COX CABLE COMMUNICATIONS INC; 
KCAL (TELEVISION STATION); JOURNALISM; REPORTERS; CABLE TELEVISION FRANCHISES; 
KEYT (TELEVISION STATION) 
</P>
