<P>
JAPANESE RESTAURANT CHAIN BUYS BEST WESTERN FOODS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Restaurant chain operators Kyotaru Co. said today that it has purchased Best 
Western Food Inc., a meat-processing company based in Los Angeles, for $41.26 
million to supply beef for the Japanese market. 
</P>
<P>
Japan, under pressure from the United States, agreed in 1988 to drop quotas on 
imported beef products by April 1, 1991. 
</P>
<P>
In response, Japanese food companies have been actively buying ranches overseas 
to continue to supply beef to their customers through Japanese sources. 
</P>
<P>
Best Western will supply beef to the Kyotaru restaurant chain, according to 
reports in the Nihon Keizai Shimbun and the Kyodo News Service. 
</P>
<P>
Kyotaru spokesman Masakazu Yoda said the company has not decided if it will 
import beef for other distribution purposes through Best Western. 
</P>
<P>
Yoda said that Robert Wiviodt, Best Western's president, has been replaced but 
that other management-level employees will remain with the company. 
</P>
<P>
Best Western had sales of $66.13 million in 1989, according to Kyotaru. 
</P>
</TEXT>
